Brian, (aka Doc Del), let's stop this now.  It serves neither of us, and will only encourage those that neither of us wish to be so encouraged. This sideline debate is becoming a estoteric mini-issue, and way outside of the scope of this thread.  If you want to continue this ala e-mail, I accept. I think, that we bore our brothers, meanwhile, with which came first, the bigot or the biggoted, the victim or the attacker.  I don't know.<br><br>
When you say you grieve for both Jew and Arab, you clearly move to a different, and perhaps higher, ground than I can.  I can not, nor will I say that.  I simply can't.  I don't grieve for my dead relatives, that is a thing long gone, but the memory continues, hence the slogan &quot;Never Again&quot; for the Jewish Defense League.  <br><br>
The lessons from the Holecaust are that first you demonize a people, then you seperate them, isolate them, turn them into the scapegoat for all the ill's of your culture or society, than dehumanize them (i.e. numbers tattoed on arms, yellow stars sewed on clothing) to further distance them from the human race. Names become numbers which makes for murdering easier. Once that is accomplished, killing them off, like rats in a lab, becomes that much easier.  Read some of the works about &quot;every german an executioner&quot; or Victor Frankl's monumental book, Man's Search for Meaning. He survived the camps, he developed the concept of the &quot;only two races, the decent and the indecent&quot;.  <br><br>
Damn it Brian, just look at Peru and what happened in the rescue.  One rebel could not kill his hostage as ordered, at the last moments, because they had &quot;humanized&quot; each other.  Never, brother, never think you can teach me anything about the camps of WW2.  I know more than you can dream, or nightmare about, but that is totally not what we are about here. Here we are about us, and a war, and our generation, and the wounds that we both endure.  Not history, but present reality.<br><br>
If I openned this Pandora's box than let me close it.  It has nothing to do with the 6 million (actually 14 million if you count gypsy's, homosexuals, politicals, etc.).  Staggers the mind, doesn't it. 14 fucking million people killed, murdered, by a Country (note I do not say a political party or a particular leader) gone biserk.  Nuff said.  <br><br>
What I was trying to tell you, to offer a compliment to you actually, is that (in my mind and maybe wrong) that I picture Hawaii as much more a blend of many cultures, and they seem to co exist well.  I live in white bread Orange County, we don't have the racial blend here, just Mexicans who cut lawns or who seek sweat shop jobs, or hang out on corners as day laborers, and a few token Blacks. <br><br>
And Little Saigon, the biggest enclave of Vietnamese in the USA I believe, but they do not assimilate, YET. They do not mix, they keep to themselves on the other side of the county from me.  Other than the signs on the freeway, I do not see them.  I think this is NOT GOOD for the ultimate assimilation into becoming American citizens.  I don't care that they are here. There's room. I care that they contribute to the greater good.  My interactions with them are limited, in comparison to yours, and after re-thinking, I posted that I don't really have a data base to offer thoughts off of. The Univ of Cal at Irvine is 15 minutes from my house, and is 45% Asian (student population). I respect that drive to study and succeed. What a great work ethic.  I am troubled that my son will probably not get in, because I can't get him to adopt that ethic.  So, in this case, I admire, not resent.<br><br>
So Doc Del, what is really lighting your fuse re: me????<br><br>
Intimidate you, I hardly think I have that power. Learn from you, Yes, that is my goal.  I have learned more on this site, in my guts, in 6 months, than I thought was possible. And yes, Brian, you are a great teacher, when you are not flaming off at me.  Is this a &quot;getting too close&quot; issue between us?  Think about it.  Why the push away?  Sorry, I am sounding like a shrink again, but I told you, I can't help that some times.<br><br>
I don't have enough branchwater to wage another Friday night, so I am off to the store.  You know that this site is addictive.  In the future, will WWW sites have to have a warning label from the Surgeon General too?<br><br>
Spatz
